{{For|the book by Canadian poet Christian Bök|Eunoia (book)}} {{Italic title}} In [[rhetoric]], '''''eunoia''''' ({{lang-grc|[[wikt:εὔνοια|εὔνοιᾰ]]|eúnoia|well mind; beautiful thinking}})<ref name="BBC2008">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_7697000/7697762.stm|title=Beautiful vowels|work=[[Today (BBC Radio 4)]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|quote=Eunoia is the shortest word in English containing all five vowels - and it means "beautiful thinking". It is also the title of Canadian poet Christian Bok's book of fiction in which each chapter uses only one vowel.}}</ref> is the [[Social capital|goodwill]] a speaker cultivates between themself and their audience, a condition of receptivity.<ref name="Garver1994">{{cite book|isbn=9780226284255|title=Aristotle's Rhetoric: An Art of Character|last=Garver|first=Eugene|location=[[Chicago]]|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|date=1994|page=112}}</ref> In Book VIII of the ''[[Nicomachean Ethics]]'', [[Aristotle]] uses the term to refer to the kind and benevolent feelings of goodwill a [[spouse]] has which form the basis for the [[ethical]] foundation of human life.<ref>[https://www.mun.ca/animus/2001vol6/provencal6.htm The Family In Aristotle<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Cicero]] translates {{lang|grc|εὔνοιᾰ}} with the [[Latin]] word {{lang|la|[[wikt:benevolentia|benevolentia]]}}.<ref>Gloria Vivenza, "Classical Roots of Benevolence in Economic Thought," ''Ancient Economic Thought'' (Routledge, 1997) pp. 198–199, 204–208 [https://books.google.com/books?id=OKxA6ibIQcYC&pg=PA205&dq=benevolentia&lr=lang_en&as_drrb_is=b&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=1932&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=2010&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=11#v=onepage&q=benevolentia&f=false online]; Cicero's influence on [[Church Fathers|patristic]] usage, Carolinne White, ''Christian Friendship in the Fourth Century'' (Cambridge University Press, 1992, 2002), pp. 16–17 [https://books.google.com/books?id=cqv_UlNH-qIC&pg=RA1-PA16&dq=benevolentia&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=17#v=onepage&q=benevolentia&f=false online], 32, and p. 255, note 13.</ref>
It is also a rarely-used [[medical term]] referring to a state of normal [[mental health]].<ref>[http://cancerweb.ncl.ac.uk/cgi-bin/omd?eunoia Definition: eunoia from Online Medical Dictionary]</ref> ''Eunoia'' is the shortest [[English language|English]] word containing all five main [[vowel]] [[graphemes]].<ref name="BBC2008"/>
==In popular culture== *''[[Eunoia (book)|Eunoia]]'' is a work by [[poet]] [[Christian Bök]] consisting of five chapters, each one using only one vowel. *In the science-fiction television series ''[[Earth: Final Conflict]]'', Eunoia is the name of the native language of the Taelon race. Bök was a consultant on that series and helped develop the language. *The debut album of math rock band Invalids. *In December 2015, the Ministry of Education in Singapore unveiled the name of a new junior College set to open in 2017, [[Eunoia Junior College]]. The unfamiliar name generated significant buzz in the Singapore community when it was first announced,<ref>[http://mothership.sg/2015/12/theres-going-to-be-a-new-junior-college-called-eunoia-heres-how-to-pronounce-it/ There’s going to be a new junior college called Eunoia; here’s how to pronounce it]</ref> including memes referencing [[Singlish]] [[homophones]].<ref>[http://sgag.sg/posts/what-kinda-weird-school-name-is-this-la-sial What kinda weird school name is this la sial?!]</ref>
